The Macedonian people voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether they wanted to change their name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that had blocked applications for EU and NATO membership.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents allege that the change would harm the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts about whether the result will reach the minimum 50 percent needed for the referendum to be valid.
