While Ri resumed the already well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" denuclearization by which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as had been the case with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean Peninsula while Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal of coercive action, even if it opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream, for those who do not know us.
But the problem is that continued sanctions only exacerbate our distrust.
Ri did not mention plans for the second Kim-Trump summit that the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier in the week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the other side of this denuclearization issue was South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have reached a dead end".
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after the "evil" President Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for her bravery in taking steps to disarm, but said there was still much work to be done and that sanctions should be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
Trump said Wednesday that there was no deadline for that, and that it would take two years, three years, five months".
China and Russia are debating whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, on Thursday US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council that: "Enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must continue firmly and without exception until we observe complete, final and verified denuclearization".
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut off funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
