Harvard students are running a course on getting enough rest.
This year, a new course at Harvard University is getting all of its students to sleep more in order to combat the growing culture of male-dominated all-night caffeinated study.
One scholar found that students at the world's top university often lack basic knowledge about how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Muller Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
She was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
"At the end of the class, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I only being told this now, in my senior year?'
He said that no one had told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first launched this year, explains to students the basics about how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had significant sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
One section is a picture of a dormitory, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it's not going to change student behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this information, just as we have a right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke", Professor Czeisler added.
The pride culture of staying up all night, he says, still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students that sleep deprivation entailed was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you get enough and good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he notes, and even to prevent weight gain, since lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, which makes you hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to run a course across the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting a bedtime alarm as well as a wake-up call, and that students be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disturb circadian rhythms and cause sleep problems.
