What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that has an impressive lineup of stars performing and an equally impressive mission to end global poverty.
In its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will see thousands of people flock to the Great Lawn area of Central Park, not only to enjoy performances by the likes of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness about the event's real goal of ending poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless they want to pay for a VIP ticket), the audience had to complete a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call, or any other meaningful way to help raise awareness about their goal of ending poverty.
But what is the success rate of Global Citizen 12 years after achieving its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a genuine way to persuade people to ask for action or is it just another case of so-called "clictivism", people who think they make a difference by signing a petition online or by sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen says it has recorded more than 19 million "shares" from its followers, driving a different set of goals.
It claims that these actions helped spur world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion set to impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
As of early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements derived from its shares, of which at least $10 billion had already been disbursed or collected.
The group estimates that so far the guaranteed funds have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor and implementing society that has pledged to "help children develop to their full potential", pledging to provide Rwanda $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizen.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national authorities and Global Citizen supporters like yourself, we can turn the social injustice of malnutrition into a footnote of history", The Power of Nutrition ambassador Tracey Ullman told the crowd during a live concert in April 2018 in London.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions were taken to improve maternal and child nutrition in the UK, the government announced funding for The Power of Nutrition project that will reach 5 million women and children with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on his website, "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen responded: "It will be a long and difficult journey, and sometimes we will fall and fail.
But just as it was with the great anti-apartheid and civil rights movements that came before us, we will succeed, because together, we are stronger.
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monae are among the artists performing at this year's event in New York, which will be hosted by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
