Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project of this technology legend, is a company based on Solid, Berners-Lee's open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people can access what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee has hinted that Inrupt's intent is to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it", he said of the startup.
"This is a historic moment".
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own "personal online data warehouse" or POD.
Contacts, to-do lists, calendars, music, and other personal and professional tools may be included.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser at the same time.
What makes this personal data store unique is that the user has complete control over who can access what information.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data".
The idea of Inrupt, according to its president John Bruce, is that the company contributes the appropriate resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security company owned by IBM, some developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, developers around the world could create their own decentralized applications with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee stated that neither he nor his team had spoken to "Facebook nor Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change that would change their business models overnight.
"We don't need your permission".
In an article published Saturday in Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial power and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of a new Solid-based web".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by establishing the World Wide Web Consortium community at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has emerged as an influential voice in the debate over net neutrality.
Even during the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium community, as well as the Web Foundation and Open Data Institute organizations.
"I'm very optimistic about this new era of the web", Berners-Lee added.
