Germany's new battleship postponed once again
The newest frigate in the German Navy was due to be delivered in 2014, to replace the old Cold War-era warships, but will not arrive until at least next year due to faulty systems and the rising cost, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class flamenco frigates, has been delayed until the first half of 2019, a military spokesman told Die Zeit newspaper.
The ship was supposed to be commissioned into the Navy in 2014, but post-delivery problems affected the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class vessels, which the Navy commissioned in 2007, will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, with different anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as with concealment technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, it should be possible to deploy the younger frigates for up to two years outside of home ports.
However, as Die Zeit points out, these continuing delays mean that the warships with the latest technology, which will allow Germany to project its power abroad, will be obsolete when they enter service.
The ill-fated F125 made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a builder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons behind this return, but German media reported "crucial defects in software and hardware" that made it impossible to use the warship on a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of 120 sailors; that is, half the personnel needed on the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, the ship was found to have a dramatic overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add improvements in the future.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to weigh twice as much as similar class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the total cost of the project, which includes crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached the staggering sum of 3.100 billion euros, compared with the initial 2.2 billion.
The problems of the newer frigates are gaining particular prominence in light of recent warnings that German naval power is making waves.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, acknowledged that the navy is running out of ships fit for deployment.
The official says this problem is growing, as old ships have been removed but not replaced by new ones.
He also regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
A new study being conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to forage.
The results are expected to shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as the bats Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys with manual detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and what each species is doing.
Then a habitat map will be drawn up to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation and what is the best way to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works that affect their young and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and aluminum foil also pose a risk, as do glue-laced fly traps, some chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when hunting.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who periodically conduct surveys, inspections of children, and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organisation even has Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, estate manager, says this is the ideal territory for them.
"In Threave we have a large bat area", he says.
"We have old buildings, historic trees, and a wonderful habitat.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats yet, so the work we're doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive".
It highlights the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the property, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single mother's nest could kill up to 400 females and young, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, or molest them, as well as to destroy their young.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, urges people to help:
"There is still much to be learned about bats, and for many of the species, we don't know how their populations are doing".
